shadow.field: A metal block that houses all the movement components.
Fifth element of the gear train, either driven by the smaller wheel of the cannon pinion, or by the sliding pinion in setting mode.

Fourth element of the gear train, consisting of a tube holding the minute hand and two wheels stacked against one another. The larger wheel is driven by the third wheel, while the smaller wheel drives the minute wheel. The smaller wheel is alternatively driven by the minute wheel in setting mode.
Attaches to the clutch and holds the cannon pinion and stem in place.
Holds up the coil assembly and houses the rotor.
Holds the wheel train in place and houses the stem mechanism.
Magnetic device with polarized sides, which rotates as the coil pulses each second, driving the wheels starting with the intermediate wheel.
Third element of the wheel train, driven by the second wheel.
Second element of the wheel train, driven by the intermediate wheel. Holds seconds hand.
First element of the wheel train, driven by the rotor.
Train Wheel Bridge Assembly. Holds the wheel train together and houses the jewels.
Props up the train wheel bridge.
Joins the battery bridle and ECB to the main plate.
Joins the coil guard, coil assembly, and stator to the main plate.
Joins the TWB to the main plate, separated by the TWB banking.
Joins the TWB to clutch and the main assembly.
Joins the clutch to the main assembly.
An electric signal is supplied here in one-second bursts from the ECB, producing a magnetic field which turns the rotor.
Center Second Stop Level. Stops the wheel train in setting mode.

Electronic Circuit Board assembly. Electricity from the battery passes through a small quartz crystal, causing it to oscillate at 32,768 Hz. The signal generated then passes through a series of switches, which reduce it to 1 Hz (once per second), before powering the coil.
Electric Module screw. Joins the coil guard, ECB, coil assembly, and stator to the main plate.
Supplies electrical power to the movement.
Prevents the battery from slipping off the side of the movement.
An extension that moves the sliding pinion. When pulled, a mechanism pushes the pinion to link with the minute wheel.
In setting mode, it links with the minute wheel and drives it when the stem is rotated.
Attaches to the stem to allow users to pull the stem and twist to set the movement.
Sixth element of the gear train, detached from the movement, but driven by the minute wheel and holding the hour hand.
